  "prompt": "What is the best way to clean house windows?",
  "response": "Cleaning house windows effectively requires the right tools, techniques, and a bit of patience. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to achieve streak-free, sparkling windows:\n\n### **1. Gather Your Supplies**  \n- **Microfiber cloths or squeegee** (for streak-free cleaning)  \n- **Window cleaner** (commercial or DIY: mix 1 part vinegar with 3 parts water)  \n- **Bucket** (for your cleaning solution)  \n- **Sponge or scrubber** (for stubborn dirt)  \n- **Lint-free cloth or newspaper** (for drying)  \n- **Extension pole** (for high or hard-to-reach windows)  \n\n### **2. Choose the Right Weather**  \nAvoid cleaning windows on sunny or windy days. Sun can dry the cleaning solution too quickly, leaving streaks, while wind can blow dirt onto the wet windows.\n\n### **3. Start with Dry Cleaning**  \nUse a dry cloth or brush to remove loose dirt, dust, or cobwebs from the window frames and sills.\n\n### **4. Apply the Cleaning Solution**  \nSpray the window cleaner generously onto the glass or apply it with a sponge. For large windows, work in sections to prevent the solution from drying too quickly.\n\n### **5. Scrub if Necessary**  \nFor stubborn grime or sticky spots, use a non-abrasive scrubber or sponge to gently remove the dirt.\n\n### **6. Use a Squeegee or Microfiber Cloth**  \n- **With a squeegee:** Start at the top corner and pull it down in a straight line, wiping the blade with a cloth after each stroke. Overlap each stroke slightly to avoid streaks.  \n- **With a microfiber cloth:** Wipe in an \"S\" pattern to prevent streaks, and use a dry cloth to buff any remaining moisture.  \n\n### **7. Dry and Polish**  \nUse a lint-free cloth or crumpled newspaper to wipe away any remaining moisture and polish the glass to a sparkling finish.\n\n### **8. Clean the Window Frames and Sills**  \nWipe down the frames and sills with a damp cloth to remove any dirt or residue.\n\n### **Tips for Success**  \n- Clean one side of the window horizontally and the other vertically to identify which side has streaks.  \n- For outdoor windows, use a ladder safely or an extension pole with a squeegee attachment.  \n- Regularly clean your tools to avoid transferring dirt back onto the windows.  \n\nWith these steps, your windows should be clean, clear, and streak-free!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
